Since cats and dogs made up about 95% of all animals, we decided to only use cats and dogs for this project.

Collapsing Factors

## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   intakereason        n  prop
##   <chr>           <int> <dbl>
## 1 Stray           55199 73.7 
## 2 Owner Surrender 14690 19.6 
## 3 Other            5015  6.70

The intake reasons were condensed into 3 main reasons, the top 2 being surrender by owner and the animal being a stray with everything else condensed into the other category.

Formulation without Interaction

Our response variable for the multinomial regression will be the intake reason for an animals and the predictors will be the animals breed, sex, and age.

\[ \begin{cases} Y_i \sim_{i.i.d} Multinomial(p_{i,1}, \ p_{i,2}, \ p_{i,3}), \ where \ Y_i = Intake \ Reason \\ \\ log(\frac{p_{ij}} {p_{i3}}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot Breed_{Dog,i} + \beta_2 \cdot Sex_{Male,i} + \beta_3 \cdot Sex_{Unknown,i} + \beta_4 \cdot Age_i\ , \ i =1,...,n \\ \\ p_{i3} = 1 - \sum_{\ell=1}^2 \ p_{i\ell} = 1 - (p_{i1} + p_{i2}) \end{cases} \]

Formulation with Interaction

\[ \begin{cases} Y_i \sim_{i.i.d} Multinomial(p_{i,1}, \ p_{i,2}, \ p_{i,3}), \ where \ Y_i = Intake \ Reason \\ \\ log(\frac{p_{ij}}{p_{i3}}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot Breed_{Dog,i} + \beta_2 \cdot Sex_{Male,i} + \beta_3 \cdot Sex_{Unknown,i} \ + \\ \beta_4 \cdot Age_i\ + \beta_5 (Breed_{Dog,i} \times Age_i), \ i = 1,...,n \\ \\ p_{i3} = 1 - \sum_{\ell=1}^2 \ p_{i\ell} = 1 - (p_{i1} + p_{i2}) \end{cases} \]

Multinomial Regression

Our primary interest is seeing if we can use an animals breed, sex, and age to predict their intake reason at the shelter.

## multinom(formula = intakereason ~ animal_type + sex + age2, data = animals)

## AIC: 104767.8

$$ log() = 2.39 - 1.29 Breed_{Dog} - 0.34 Sex_{Male} - 1.57 Sex_{Unknown} - 0.05 Age \

log() = 3.74 - 1.21 Breed_{Dog} - 0.21 Sex_{Male} + 0.62 Sex_{Unknown} - 0.13 Age $$

Interpretations

Surrendered by Owner

Age: Per 1 year increase in age, the odds of the intake reason being that the animal was surrendered by the owner as opposed to being one of the other reasons multiply by \(e^{-0.05}\), holding all else constant.

Dog: The odds a dog is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to other reasons are \(e^{-1.29}\) times that of a cat, holding all else constant.

Sex (Male): The odds a male cat or dog is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to other reasons multiply by \(e^{-0.34}\) times that of a female cat or dog, holding all else constant.

Sex (Unknown): The odds a cat or dog with unknown sex is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to other reasons multiply by \(e^{-1.57}\) times that of a female cat or dog, holding all else constant.

Stray

Age: Per 1 year increase in age, the odds of the intake reason being that the animal was a stray as opposed to being one of the other reasons multiply by \(e^{-0.13}\), holding all else constant.

Dog: The odds of a dog being taken in because it was a stray as opposed to being one of the other reasons are \(e^{-1.21}\) times that of a cat, holding all else constant.

Sex (Male): The odds a male cat or dog is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to other reasons multiply by \(e^{-0.21}\) times that of a female cat or dog, holding all else constant.

Sex (Unknown): The odds a cat or dog with unknown sex is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to other reasons multiply by \(e^{0.62}\) times that of a female cat or dog, holding all else constant.

Interpretation of a CI for animal surrendered by owner:

Male: We are 95% confident that the odds that a male cat or dog is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to one of the other reasons multiply by between (\(e^{-0.403}\), \(e^{-0.272}\)), holding all else constant.

\[ log(\frac{ \hat{p_{Surrender}} } {\hat{ p_{Other}} }) = 2.42 - 1.23 \cdot Breed_{Dog} - 0.34 \cdot Sex_{Male} - 1.57 \cdot Sex_{Unknown} - 0.05 \cdot Age\ \\ - 0.03 (Breed_{Dog} \times Age) \\ log(\frac{ \hat{p_{Stray}} } {\hat{ p_{Other}} }) = 3.95 - 1.5 \cdot Breed_{Dog} - 0.22 \cdot Sex_{Male} + 0.56 \cdot Sex_{Unknown} - 0.23 \cdot Age\ \\ + 0.12 (Breed_{Dog} \times Age) \]

Interpretations (with interaction term)

Surrendered by Owner

Age: Per 1 year increase in age, the odds of the intake reason being that the animal was surrendered by the owner as opposed to being one of the other reasons multiply by \(e^{-0.23 + 0.12 \cdot Breed}\), holding all else constant.

Dog: The odds a dog is taken in because their owner surrendered them as opposed to other reasons are \(e^{-1.23-0.03 \cdot Age}\) times that of a cat, holding all else constant.

Sex (Male): The odds a male cat or dog is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to other reasons multiply by \(e^{-0.34}\) times that of a female cat or dog, holding all else constant.

Sex (Unknown): The odds a cat or dog with unknown sex is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to other reasons multiply by \(e^{-1.57}\) times that of a female cat or dog, holding all else constant.

Stray

Dog: The odds of a dog being taken in because it was a stray as opposed to being one of the other reasons are \(e^{-1.5+0.12 \cdot Age}\) times that of a cat, holding all else constant.

Age: Per 1 year increase in age, the odds of the intake reason being that the animal was a stray as opposed to being one of the other reasons multiply by \(e^{-0.05 - 0.03 \cdot Breed}\), holding all else constant.

Sex (Male): The odds a male cat or dog is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to other reasons multiply by \(e^{-0.22}\) times that of a female cat or dog, holding all else constant.

Sex (Unknown): The odds a cat or dog with unknown sex is taken in because their owner wanted to get rid of them as opposed to other reasons multiply by \(e^{0.56}\) times that of a female cat or dog, holding all else constant.

Testing each predictor as a whole

To test each predictor as a whole, we perform the Likelihood Ratio Test.

Anova(fit)
## Analysis of Deviance Table (Type II tests)
## 
## Response: intakereason
##                  LR Chisq Df Pr(>Chisq)    
## animal_type       1106.98  2  < 2.2e-16 ***
## sex                739.55  4  < 2.2e-16 ***
## age2              1390.21  2  < 2.2e-16 ***
## animal_type:age2   683.57  2  < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# z scores
z <- round(summary(fit)$coefficients / summary(fit)$standard.errors,3)

# p values
p <- (1 - pnorm(abs(z), 0, 1)) * 2
#p

We can see that all of the predictors are statistically significant.

A very large LRT stat indicates strong evidence against \(H_0: \{All \ \beta_{ij}'s = 0 \} vs. H_a: \{At \ least \ one \ \beta_{ij} \ \not = 0 \}\)

Effect Display

This effect plot plots the probability of an intake reason by age for animal type. We can see that for cats, stray and surrendered by owner are inverses. As a cat gets older, the probability of the intake reason being that it was surrendered by owner increases, while the probability of the intake reason being stray decreases as a cat gets older.

Time Series

For the time series portion, we are trying to forecast the number of animals brought into the animal shelter a year into the future. We will do this by breaking our data into a train set and a test set and compare at the end.

The inital time series plot had some non-constant variance, so a BoxCox transformation was applied in order to reduce some of the non-constant variance.

First, we checked to see if there was any seasonal differencing that needed to be done. We applied one seasonal differencing to stabilize the mean of the time series. Then we used the display to decide on an ARIMA model. ARIMA(0,0,0)(0,1,1) was the model we came up with based on the ACF and PACF plots.

ARIMA models

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(0,0,0)(0,1,0)[12]
## Q* = 10.445, df = 11, p-value = 0.4908
## 
## Model df: 0.   Total lags used: 11

Now we check the residuals of our ARIMA model to see if the fitted residuals are white noise or not. The mean is roughly 0 and the variance is a little shaky but not too bad. From the ACF plot, all the ACFs except one are within the white noise bands, and the residuals are normally distriubted. The Ljung-Box Test has a high p-value of about 0.5, thus we fail to reject the null hypothesis of the residuals being white noise.

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(0,0,0)(1,1,0)[12] with drift
## Q* = 5.9926, df = 9, p-value = 0.7407
## 
## Model df: 2.   Total lags used: 11

Then we tried the R function that chooses, what it thinks to be, the best ARIMA model for the given data. Here it chooses the ARIMA(0,0,0)(1,1,0)[12] model. It meets all the same criteria (mean and variance stabilization, ACFs being within the bands, and the residuals being normally distributed) compared to the other model, but the p-value is higher. So we will go with this ARIMA model.

Forecasting

For the forecasting, we break up our data into a training set and a test set. The trianing set runs from October 2010 to February 2017. The test set is just the last year in the data, from March 2017 to March 2018.

The accuracy of our forecasts are shown below. Even though it says Training set it is actually the accuracy of the test set. We will only interpret RMSE and MAPE as an example and also because RMSE is scale dependent and MAPE is not.

RMSE: The forecasted values miss the actual number of intakes by 65.1 intakes, on average.

MAPE: The forecasted values miss the actual number of intakes by 2.2%, on average.
